<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1565,2022]" pageId="1" pageNumber="335">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,260,1565,1590]" pageId="1" pageNumber="335">Remarks</emphasis>
. As mentioned in the description given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Viraktamath" box="[756,1117,1565,1590]" pageId="1" pageNumber="335" refString="Viraktamath, C. A. &amp; Mohan, G. S. (2004) A revision of the deltocephaline leafhopper genus Scaphoideus (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae) from the Indian subcontinent. Zootaxa, 578, 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="2004">
Viraktamath and Mohan (
<number box="[1048,1109,1566,1590]" pageId="1" pageNumber="335" value="2004.0">2004</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, the species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1294,1436,1565,1589]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1294,1436,1565,1589]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="335">Scaphoideus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differ widely in colour and male genitalia, and can be divided into three groups according to coloration: (
<number box="[1350,1362,1602,1626]" pageId="1" pageNumber="335" value="1.0">1</number>
) body ochraceous to brown with a median longitudinal yellowish or whitish stripe extending to folded front wings; (
<number box="[1412,1427,1638,1662]" pageId="1" pageNumber="335" value="2.0">2</number>
) body with transverse bands on vertex, pronotum and scutellum; (
<number box="[875,889,1674,1698]" pageId="1" pageNumber="335" value="3.0">3</number>
) body with dark brown spots or bands on vertex, and longitudinal bands on pronotum and scutellum. In the first group, here referred to as the 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albovittatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="335">Scaphoideus albovittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, species are very similar in coloration and difficult to distinguish externally. Based on the number of spots on vertex and male genitalia, they can be divided into two morphotypes: 
<number box="[1166,1178,1782,1806]" pageId="1" pageNumber="335" value="1.0">1</number>
) Vertex pale with four spots; style with preapical lobe not developed; subgenital plate with blunt distal end; and aedeagus without process, including S. 
<taxonomicName box="[298,398,1854,1877]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostratus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[298,398,1854,1877]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="335">rostratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[408,500,1853,1878]" pageId="1" pageNumber="335" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[408,500,1853,1878]" pageId="1" pageNumber="335">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Matsumura" authorityName="Matsumura" box="[516,816,1853,1877]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albovittatus">
<emphasis box="[516,680,1853,1877]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="335">S. albovittatus</emphasis>
Matsumura
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[875,995,1853,1877]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="katraini">
<emphasis box="[875,995,1853,1877]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="335">S. katraini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<number box="[1012,1027,1854,1878]" pageId="1" pageNumber="335" value="2.0">2</number>
) Vertex pale with three spots; style with preapical lobe well developed; subgenital plate with round distal end and aedeagus with pair of processes; including other nine species as in checklist.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1565,2022]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,151,320]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="336" pageId="1" pageNumber="335">
The known females of Chinese species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[721,1002,1961,1985]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albovittatus">
<emphasis box="[721,1002,1961,1985]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="335">Scaphoideus albovittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group can be distinguished from each other mainly by the following characters: the posterior margin of sternite VII is well produced medially and forms a median lobe in 
<taxonomicName box="[349,476,152,175]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="336" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coniceus">
<emphasis box="[349,476,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="336">S. coniceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[493,562,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1269,1291]" captionTargetBox="[170,1416,303,1231]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[170,1417,303,1246]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Female abdomen and sternite VII, ventral view. A – D. Female abdomen, ventral view; E – H. Sternite VII, ventral view. A, E. S. albovittatus; B, F. S. coniceus; C, G. S. kumamotonis; D, H. S. maai." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/233534/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="336">
Fig. 
<number box="[546,562,152,176]" pageId="2" pageNumber="336" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
B, F), 
<taxonomicName box="[634,720,152,175]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="336" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maai">
<emphasis box="[634,720,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="336">S. maai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[736,805,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1269,1291]" captionTargetBox="[170,1416,303,1231]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[170,1417,303,1246]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Female abdomen and sternite VII, ventral view. A – D. Female abdomen, ventral view; E – H. Sternite VII, ventral view. A, E. S. albovittatus; B, F. S. coniceus; C, G. S. kumamotonis; D, H. S. maai." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/233534/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="336">
Fig. 
<number box="[790,805,152,176]" pageId="2" pageNumber="336" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
D, H), 
<taxonomicName box="[884,1046,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="336" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intermedius">
<emphasis box="[884,1046,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="336">S. intermedius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1103,1281,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="336" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kumamotonis">
<emphasis box="[1103,1281,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="336">S. kumamotonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1298,1366,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1269,1291]" captionTargetBox="[170,1416,303,1231]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[170,1417,303,1246]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Female abdomen and sternite VII, ventral view. A – D. Female abdomen, ventral view; E – H. Sternite VII, ventral view. A, E. S. albovittatus; B, F. S. coniceus; C, G. S. kumamotonis; D, H. S. maai." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/233534/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="336">
Fig. 
<number box="[1351,1366,152,176]" pageId="2" pageNumber="336" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
C, G), and the former species has the projection slightly elongated (
<figureCitation box="[881,954,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1269,1291]" captionTargetBox="[170,1416,303,1231]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[170,1417,303,1246]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Female abdomen and sternite VII, ventral view. A – D. Female abdomen, ventral view; E – H. Sternite VII, ventral view. A, E. S. albovittatus; B, F. S. coniceus; C, G. S. kumamotonis; D, H. S. maai." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/233534/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="336">
Fig. 
<number box="[938,954,188,212]" pageId="2" pageNumber="336" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
B, F), the last species has the projection conspicuous more elongated with a notch in the middle (
<figureCitation box="[782,849,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1269,1291]" captionTargetBox="[170,1416,303,1231]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[170,1417,303,1246]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Female abdomen and sternite VII, ventral view. A – D. Female abdomen, ventral view; E – H. Sternite VII, ventral view. A, E. S. albovittatus; B, F. S. coniceus; C, G. S. kumamotonis; D, H. S. maai." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/233534/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="336">
Fig. 
<number box="[834,849,224,248]" pageId="2" pageNumber="336" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
C, G); in 
<taxonomicName box="[952,1112,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="336" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albovittatus">
<emphasis box="[952,966,224,247]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="336">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[980,1112,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="336">albovittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1127,1194,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1269,1291]" captionTargetBox="[170,1416,303,1231]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[170,1417,303,1246]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Female abdomen and sternite VII, ventral view. A – D. Female abdomen, ventral view; E – H. Sternite VII, ventral view. A, E. S. albovittatus; B, F. S. coniceus; C, G. S. kumamotonis; D, H. S. maai." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/233534/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="336">
Fig. 
<number box="[1179,1194,224,248]" pageId="2" pageNumber="336" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
A, E), the sternite VII is broadly convex and lacks a distinct median lobe, and deeply incised in the middle. Other characteristics are similar among females.
</paragraph>
